data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The `AllowSynchronousIO` / sync-over-async escape hatch that worked in .NET 10 no longer exists.

Every synchronous LINQ operator (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime — there is no configuration to re-enable them.

## The fix: go fully async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`
- `ToList` → `ToListAsync`, `First` → `FirstAsync`, `Count` → `CountAsync`, `SaveChanges` → `SaveChangesAsync`
- All callers up the chain must also become async (`async` propagates upward)

The async methods come from `Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore` — make sure you have `using Microsoft.EntityFrameworkCore;` at the top.
